# üêß Linux Practice ‚Äì File Viewing and Editing Commands

## Topic
vi, cat, less, more, head, tail

## Practice Exercises

1. Create a new file named `notes.txt` using the vi editor.
2. Open `notes.txt` in vi and write at least five lines of text.
3. Save the file and exit the vi editor.
4. Reopen `notes.txt` using vi.
5. Edit one existing line in the file.
6. Save the changes and exit.

7. Display the complete contents of `notes.txt` using the cat command.
8. Display the contents of `notes.txt` with line numbers.
9. Create another file named `data.txt` with multiple lines of text.
10. Display both `notes.txt` and `data.txt` together using a single command.

11. View the contents of `notes.txt` using the more command.
12. Scroll through `notes.txt` using the less command.
13. Exit from the less command after viewing the file.

14. Display the first 5 lines of `notes.txt`.
15. Display the first 10 lines of `notes.txt`.

16. Display the last 5 lines of `notes.txt`.
17. Display the last 10 lines of `notes.txt`.

18. Add more lines of text to `notes.txt` using the vi editor.
19. View only the last few lines of `notes.txt` after the update.
20. Observe the difference between head and tail commands.

21. View a large file using more and navigate through it.
22. View the same file using less and compare the behavior.
23. Identify one advantage of using less over more.

24. Display a specific number of lines from the beginning of a file.
25. Display a specific number of lines from the end of a file.
